Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Airways, First Bank, Sterling

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-14T16:41:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-airways-naiade-resorts-move.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index advanced for a third day, adding 0.4 percent to
24,916.97 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a
statement on the bourse’s website.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index gained for a second day, adding
0.3 percent to 2,053.57 at the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis ,
the highest since Feb. 21. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index fell for a second day 0.3 percent to 1,043.34 at the 3
p.m. close in Accra.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
climbed less than 0.1 percent to 876.21 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. Kenya’s All-Share Index was unchanged at 74.12 at the
3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Access Kenya Group Ltd. (ACCESS KN), the nation’s only
publicly traded Internet company, slumped 7 cents, or 6.8
percent, to 9.6 shillings, on speculation it may not have
returned to profit in the first quarter.  “Quarter one has been difficult for IT companies in terms
of margins and competition” and the company is unlikely to have
returned to profit, Victor Odendo, an analyst at Nairobi-based
Apex Africa Capital Ltd., said in a phone interview today.  First Bank of Nigeria Plc (FIRSTBAN)  , the West African
nation’s second biggest lender by market value, fell for the
first day in four, slumping 7 kobo, or 4.8 percent, to 13.88
naira, the most since Oct. 6, after it reported net income
advanced sevenfold to 33.4 billion naira, lower than the 43.8
billion naira median estimate of seven analysts polled by
Bloomberg.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL) ,, sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, jumped 1.75 shillings, or 5.3 percent, to 34.5
shillings, the biggest advance since March 15, after Managing
Director Titus Naikuni said it will buy nine new Boeing Corp.
787 aircraft an open seven new routes in 2011 and seven in 2012.
“It is good that they have cemented that deal,” Victor Odendo,
an analyst at Nairobi-based Apex Africa Capital Ltd., said in a
phone interview today. “It shows financial strength.”  Naiade Resorts Ltd. (NRL)  , Mauritius’s third-largest
hotel operator by market value, rose 0.3 rupee, or 1.1 percent,
to 27.1 rupee, after Axys Stockbroking Ltd. upgraded the stock’s
rating to “hold” from “reduce.”  “Naiade is trading at a 19 percent discount to net asset
value,” said Bhavik Desai and Vikash Tulsidas, Axys analysts.
“Its debt-to-equity ratio is expected to improve.”  Sterling Bank (STERLNBA)  Plc, a Nigerian lender, rose
for the first day in six, adding 10 kobo, or 4.6 percent, to
2.29 naira, the most since April 5. FirstRand Ltd., South
Africa’s second-biggest financial services company, said it
plans to buy a majority stake in Sterling.  United Bank for Africa Plc (UBA)  ,  Nigeria ’s fifth-
largest lender by market value, declined 9 kobo, or 1.1 percent,
to 8 naira, after it saying full-year profit for the 12 months
through Dec. 31 fell to 1.25 billion naira ($8.1 million) from
2.37 billion naira in the previous year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
